      "content": "It is indeed the dominant view among legal scholars that outdated antitrust laws require aggressive modernization to effectively halt these market consolidations. The legitimate arguments for intervention now hinge on preventing \"killer acquisitions\" where companies are bought solely to remove future competition, which stale regulations often fail to catch in time. Furthermore, regulators increasingly recognize that in digital ecosystems, allowing unchecked dominance can permanently lock out innovation rather than fueling it.",
      "source": "target",
